@node "Intro" "Introduction/Features"


Introduction


Trekkie is a database, that offers the possibility to manage all the Star Trek
episodes. Apart from collecting the usual data such as Episodetitle, -number,
Stardate and so on, it facilitates to build a kind of "Who is Who" by managing
the "Maker"-information. Moreover there is a - admittedly simple - video
database included. You can add pictures, movies or sounds to episodes and
makers, by giving Trekkie the filenames. With external Viewers/Players you can
show/play these files from Trekkie.

The datafile contains information on the different incarnations of Star Trek
on television and the big-screen and various Star Trek novels. The
"Maker"-database offers almost everything, you might want to know about the
people in front of and behind the camera.

The program requires Kickstart/Workbench 3.0.  With the enclosed datafile you
need almost 4MB of RAM at runtime. The program would run on a 68000 processor
but for acceptable performance the absolute minimum is a 68020 processor.
@endnode

@node "Install" "Installation"


To install Trekkie you can use the provided  Installer script. Just follow the
on-screen instructions. No configurations or datafiles of a previous
installation will be overwritten. If a datafile named "trek.dat" is found
during the installation it will be backed up.

When you first start Trekkie, you should correctly set up the external
programs. If you intend to change the episode descriptions you have to
configure the @{"Editor" link "Editor" 0} correctly. Do not forget to save the prefs.
@endnode

@node "Config" "Configuration"
The Preferences are stored in a seperate preferences file. Normally Trekkie
looks for a file called "Trekkie.prefs" in the program directory. If it is not
found there Trekkie looks into the ENV: directory.

You can change this behaviour if you specify the tooltype PREFSFILE, telling
Trekkie the name and path of the prefs file to use.

To change the configuration (@{"screenmode" link "ScreenMode" 0}, external viewers, @{"editor" link "Editor" 0}, default
datafile) you can use the Preferences menu in Trekkie.

When you save the prefs you should also make sure that you have selected your
prefered language for the episode descriptions. You can later easily switch
between English and German.

You can also store your favourite settings for @{"Listmask" link "Listmask" 0}, @{"Sortpattern" link "Sortpattern" 0}, and
@{"Selectionpattern" link "Selection" 0} as default, or make different patterns available on the
F1-F10 keys.
@endnode

@node "Usage" "Usage         "


The program is started by doubleclicking on its icon. If no valid @{"screenmode" link "ScreenMode" 0}
has been previously specified a requester pops up. If a default datafile is
given in the prefs, it is now loaded.  That can, depending on size of the file
and speed of your CPU,  take a short while.@{b}@{u}

Important note:@{ub}@{uu} With Trekkie 2.6 the format of the datafiles has changed
again. But now Trekkie can't directly read datafiles created with older
versions anymore. Those files must be converted. You can @{"contact me" link "Author" 0} for the
conversion tool or download it at my homepage.

Trekkie has two windows from which all other functions can be accessed. The
@{"Listmode" link "Listmode" 0} window and The @{"Editmode" link "Editmode" 0} window. On startup the Listmode is active.

Both windows feature the same menus:


@{b}@{u}Project:@{ub}@{uu}


  @{b}New@{ub}                   Starts a new project and goes to Editmode

  @{b}Load@{ub}                  Loads a datafile from disk

  @{b}Append@{ub}                Appends the data from an external file to the current
                        project (@{"Note!" link "Merge Note" 0})

  @{b}Merge@{ub}                 Adds the "personal" information from an external file
                        to the current project (@{"Note!" link "MergePersonal" 0})

  @{b}Save@{ub}                  Saves the current project

  @{b}Save As@{ub} .. @{b}All Data@{ub}   Saves the project under a given name

             @{b}Selection@{ub}  Saves only entries of current @{"selection" link "Current selection" 0}

  @{b}Print List@{ub}            @{"Prints" link "Print" 0} the current @{"selection" link "Current selection" 0} as shown on screen

  @{b}About@{ub}                 Shows a short Info about the @{"Author" link "Author" 0}

  @{b}Quit@{ub}                  Hidden secret function ;-)



@{b}@{u}Episode:@{ub}@{uu}


  @{b}New@{ub}                   Creates a new episode entry and goes to @{"Editmode" link "Editmode" 0}

  @{b}Copy@{ub}                  Copys currently selected/displayed entry and goes 
                        to @{"Editmode" link "Editmode" 0}

  @{b}Delete@{ub}                Deletes currently selected/displayed entry.

  @{b}Print@{ub}                 @{"Prints" link "Print" 0} currently selected/displayed entry.

  @{b}Pictures@{ub}              Views the pictures for the selected 
                        episode.

@{b}@{u}Display:@{ub}@{uu}


  @{b}Edit Mode@{ub}             Goes to @{"Editmode" link "Editmode" 0} with currently selected entry.

  @{b}List Mode@{ub}             Goes to @{"Listmode" link "Listmode" 0}

  @{b}All Entries @{ub}          Cancels current @{"selection" link "Current selection" 0} and displays all 
                        entries again.

  @{b}Search@{ub}                Lets you specify a @{"Selectionpattern" link "Selection" 0} and shows
                        appropriate entries in @{"Listmode" link "Listmode" 0} afterwards

  @{b}Sort@{ub}                  Lets you specify a @{"sortpattern" link "Sortpattern" 0} and appropriately
                        sorts the episodes

  @{"Listmask" link "Listmask" 0}              Lets you define the appearance of the table in
                        @{"Listmode" link "Listmode" 0}

  @{b}Load settings@{ub}         Loads the prefs for @{"Selectionpatten" link "Selection" 0}, @{"Sortpattern" link "Sortpattern" 0}
                        and @{"Listmask" link "Listmask" 0} all at once.

  @{b}Save settings@{ub}         Saves the prefs for @{"Selectionpatten" link "Selection" 0}, @{"Sortpattern" link "Sortpattern" 0}
                        and @{"Listmask" link "Listmask" 0} all at once.



@{b}@{u}Special:@{ub}@{uu}


  @{"Makerlist" link "Makerlist" 0}             Gives you a list of all or certain makers with
                        several search options

  @{b}Maker Birthdays@{ub}       Gives you a a calendrically sorted list of 
                        all makers with specified birth- and/or deathday

  @{"Maker Trek Crossovers" link "Crossover" 0} Gives you a list of all or certain makers who
                        have worked for more than one Star Trek series

  @{"Videolist" link "Videolist" 0}             Gives you a list of all or certain videos.

  @{b}Average Rating@{ub}        Calculates the average @{"Rating" link "Ratings" 0} of the curent
                        selection. A rate of 0 is not considered

  @{b}Stardate Overlaps@{ub}     Gives you a list of all episodes where the
                        previous episode ends (according to the stardate)
                        later than the next starts.

  @{b}Statistics@{ub}            Gives you some nice statistics about your database.



@{b}@{u}Preferences:@{ub}@{uu}


  @{b}DOS Search Patterns@{ub}   If checked AmigaDos @{"Searchpatterns" link "Search Patterns" 0} are used instead
                        of the built in.

  @{b}Change Screenmode@{ub}     Lets you change the @{"screenmode" link "ScreenMode" 0} of Trekkies screen.

  @{b}Set Standardfile@{ub}      Lets you chose the file that Trekkie loads on
                        startup

  @{b}External Program@{ub}      Lets you chose the @{"Editor" link "Editor" 0} for the episode
                        descriptions and the programs Trekkie uses when
                        showing pictures, playing sounds or movies.

  @{b}English Descriptions@{ub}  Select the language for the episode descriptions.
  @{b}German Descriptions@{ub}   (Make sure to save your "prefered" language.)

  @{b}Save Prefs@{ub}            Saves the above Prefs
@endnode

